text.b: PART A – PURPOSE OF REPORT AND STUDY OBJECTIVES

page.text: Wal-Mart Stores, Inc. (WalMart) is proposing a new store to be located on a parcel of land
located on the southeast corner of State Trunk Highway (STH) 64/East Main Street and Pine
Ridge Avenue in the City of Merrill, Lincoln County, Wisconsin. A traffic impact analysis
(TIA) was submitted for the new store on April 27, 2012 based on counts performed in winter
months. At the request of the Wisconsin Department of Transportation (WisDOT), this
supplemental TIA has been prepared based on updated summer counts to reflect higher volumes.
This supplemental TIA documents the procedures, findings and conclusions of the traffic
analysis. The analysis identifies recommended improvements based on existing intersection
geometrics, background traffic volumes, and additional traffic expected to be generated by the
proposed development within the limits of the study area.
The executive summary includes a description of the study area, description of the development
and conclusions based on the findings of the supplemental TIA.

page.text: The study area intersections were analyzed based on the procedures set forth in the 2010
Highway Capacity Manual (HCM). Intersection operation is defined by “level of service”.
Level of Service (LOS) is a quantitative measure that refers to the overall quality of flow at an
intersection ranging from very good, represented by LOS ‘A’, to very poor, represented by LOS
‘F’. For the purpose of this study, and per discussions with WisDOT, LOS C or better was used
to define desirable peak hour operating conditions.

A1. Development Description and Site Location

page.text: The WalMart development site is proposed to be located on the southeast corner of STH 64/East

The proposed site currently consists of a wooded lot. The development site is bordered by:

 A medical building to the west of the restaurant;

 A partially wooded lot immediately to the south;
 Commercial properties to the north and northwest.

. Two access points are proposed for the WalMart development. The first access,

as a one-way stop controlled full access point (i.e. no restrictions).

Year 2022. The first scenario assumes no changes to the existing geometrics. Scenario two

text.b: PART C – OFF-SITE LAND USE AND DEVELOPMENT

page.text: One off-site development has been identified within the limits of the study area. A 3.0 acre
parcel located on the southeast corner of STH 64 at Pine Ridge Avenue (adjacent to Outlot A) is
expected to develop over the next several years. Based on discussions with the property owner,
the following land uses were assumed to occur on the off-site parcel:
Although the off-site development will occur over the next several years it was included in the
Year 2012 summer build traffic volumes. In addition, it is noted that the existing WalMart store,
located immediately north of STH 64, is expected to redevelop into a similar use with a similar
traffic pattern and is included in the background and full build traffic volumes.
The study area roadways are discussed below:
STH 64/East Main Street is a four-lane divided east/west arterial highway from immediately
west of Pine Ridge Avenue to a point approximately 200 feet east of CTH W where it transitions
to a two-lane undivided highway to the east. West of Pine Ridge, CTH 64 is a four-lane
undivided highway as it enters the City of Merrill. STH 64 has a posted speed limit of 35 miles
per hour (mph) west of Big Eddy Road, 45-mph between Big Eddy Road and CTH W and a
posted speed limit of 55-mph to the east of CTH W. The 2010 AADT collected by WisDOT on
STH 64 was 11,100 vehicles per day (vpd) west of Big Eddy Road; 9,500-vpd west of Pine
Ridge Avenue, 7,600-vpd west of CTH W and a year 2004 AADT of 3,400-vpd east of CTH W.
STH 64 is a concrete roadway with curb and gutter west of Pine Ridge Avenue and paved and
gravel shoulders to the east through the study area.
USH 51 Interchange with STH 64 is a diamond interchange. Year 2010 AADT volumes
collected by WisDOT on the USH 51 ramps were as follows: NB off ramp was 3,700-vpd, NB
on ramp was 1,100-vpd, SB off ramp was 1,100-vpd, and SB on ramp was 3,900-vpd.
Big Eddy Road is a two-lane undivided north/south roadway that intersects with STH 64 to
create the south leg of a four legged intersection. The north leg of the intersection is designated
as Amber Street. Big Eddy Road has a rural cross-section and a posted speed limit of 35-mph
within the study area. The 2010 AADT on Big Eddy Road was 1,200-vpd south of STH 64.
Pine Ridge Avenue is a two-lane north/south roadway that intersects STH 64 immediately west
of the USH 51 SB ramps. Pine Ridge Avenue provides access to a restaurant and a medical
building and dead ends approximately 200 feet south of STH 64. To the north Pine Ridge
Avenue provides access to several commercial developments. The posted speed limit on Pine
Ridge Avenue is 25 mph. No AADT data is currently available for Pine Ridge Avenue.

text.b: PART C – CAPACITY LEVEL OF SERVICE

page.text: The study area intersections were analyzed based on the procedures set forth in the 2010
Highway Capacity Manual (HCM). Intersection operation is defined by “level of service”.
Level of service (LOS) is a quantitative measure that refers to the overall quality of flow at an
intersection ranging from very good, represented by LOS ‘A’, to very poor, represented by LOS
‘F’. For the purpose of this study, per discussions with WisDOT and per WalMart guidelines,
LOS C or better was used to define desirable peak hour operating conditions. Descriptions of the
various levels of service are as follows:
LOS A is the highest level of service that can be achieved. Under this condition,
intersection approaches appear quite open, turning movements are easily made, and
nearly all drivers find freedom of operation. At signalized and unsignalized intersections,
LOS B represents stable operation. At signalized intersections, average vehicle delays are
seconds. At unsignalized intersections, average delays are
LOS C still represents stable operation, but periodic backups of a few vehicles may
develop behind turning vehicles. Most drivers begin to feel restricted, but not
objectionably so. At signalized intersections, average vehicle delays are
seconds. At unsignalized intersections, average delays are
LOS D represents increasing traffic restrictions as the intersection approaches instability.
Delays to approaching vehicles may be substantial during short peaks within the peak
period, but periodic clearance of long lines occurs, thus preventing excessive backups.
At signalized intersections, average vehicle delays are
LOS E represents the capacity of the intersection. At signalized intersections, average
seconds. At unsignalized intersections, average delays are
LOS F represents jammed conditions where the intersection is over capacity and
acceptable gaps for unsignalized intersections in the mainline traffic flow are minimal.

text.b: B3. Determination of Linked and Pass-by Trip Traffic

page.text: An internally linked trip occurs when a patron of one tenant visits another tenant prior to exiting
the site (e.g. a WalMart patron visits the restaurant prior to entering the highway system). It is
estimated that approximately 20 percent of the commercial outlot trips will be linked trips.
A diverted linked trip occurs when a patron of an existing site visits a new site. It is estimated
that approximately 10 percent of the site generated trips (i.e. trips minus internally linked and
pass-by trips) are expected to be diverted linked trips with existing sites located north of STH 64
In addition, approximately 10-percent of the commercial driveway trips are expected to be pass-
by trips. Pass-by trips occur when motorists already on the highway system stop at a
development site prior to continuing on their intended route (e.g. an existing motorist westbound
on STH 64 stops at WalMart prior to continuing westbound on STH 64/East Main Street).
Combined pass-by trips for both on-site and off-site developments were not allowed to exceed 10
percent of the existing traffic volumes along STH 64/East Main Street, per WisDOT and ITE
The trip distribution for the WalMart development as listed below was determined based on the
existing traffic counts, the type of proposed land uses, the location of existing populations, and
anticipated growth areas outside the immediate study area.
 15-percent to/from the east on STH 64/East Main Street;
 30-percent to/from the west on STH 64/East Main Street;
 5-percent to/from the south on CTH W.
